==English==

===Etymology===
From {{der|en|la|sabbatum}} partly through {{der|en|fro|sabbat}}, {{m|fro|sabat}}, from {{der|en|grc|σάββατον||Sabbath}}, from {{der|en|he|sc=Hebr|שבת|tr=shabát||Sabbath}}.

{{etystub|en|If from Greek, then why the final th rather than t?}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈsæbəθ/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{l|en|Saturday}}, observed in {{l|en|Judaism}} and some Christian denominations as a day of rest.
# {{l|en|Sunday}}, observed in most of {{l|en|Christianity}} as a day of rest.
# {{l|en|Friday}}, observed in {{l|en|Islam}} as a day of rest.
# A meeting of {{l|en|witch|witches}}, presided over by the [[devil]]. (Also: witches' sabbath ''or'' black sabbath).
#* '''1971''', {{w|Keith Thomas (historian)|Keith Thomas}}, ''Religion and the Decline of Magic'', Folio Society 2012, page 419:
#*: Around this conception was built up the notion of ritual devil-worship, involving the '''sabbath''' or nocturnal meeting at which the witches gathered to worship their master and to copulate with him.

